The scenarios MUST name vendors from `compliance/vendors.md`. Generic "PayPal" scenarios don't land for a team that doesn't use PayPal.

Include a section on **AI-era phishing tells**:
- Voice cloning (the "founder's voice asking for a wire transfer" scenario)
- LLM-generated text without typos (no longer a tell)
- Deep-fake video on calls (verify with a known channel before acting on urgent requests)
- Spear-phish targeting from public OSS contributions (the GitHub commit history phish)

#### Topic: secure-coding

Pull real diffs from `git log`. For each major secure-coding lesson, find a real example:

```
LESSON 1 — Input validation at the trust boundary
═════════════════════════════════════════════════
Bad example (from our own git history, anonymized):
  // PR #142, reverted after /cso flagged it
  const data = JSON.parse(req.body);
  await db.query(`INSERT INTO orders (data) VALUES ('${data.payload}')`);

What's wrong:
  - No schema validation on req.body
  - String interpolation in SQL (classic injection vector)
  - data.payload could be any shape, including objects we'd serialize incorrectly

Good example (current code, post-fix):
  // src/api/orders.ts
  const parsed = OrderSchema.parse(req.body);  // zod validation
  await db.query('INSERT INTO orders (data) VALUES ($1)', [parsed.payload]);

Lesson: Validate at the trust boundary. Trust nothing from req.body until a
schema has touched it. Use parameterized queries always.

This appeared in our codebase. /cso flagged it. We fixed it. Don't reintroduce it.
```

Generate 5-7 lessons covering the categories that match Hall's actual stack:
- Input validation (universal)
- SQL / NoSQL injection (per DB)
- XSS / SSTI (per framework — React-safe by default, jinja2 NOT)
- SSRF (per HTTP client)
- Secret management (env vs hardcoded)
- Authentication boundaries (which routes need auth)
- Authorization boundaries (who can access whose data)
- LLM-specific: prompt injection if Hall ships AI features
- Rate limiting & cost containment for AI calls

Pull the BAD examples from `/cso` history if available; otherwise use canonical bad examples from OWASP. Pull the GOOD examples from current code.

